ce:section.ce:para:
Fluorescence quantum yield (ΦF) plays a critical role in anticancer therapies as it measures the sensitizer's ability to emit fluorescence, directly indicating its effectiveness in therapeutic applications. The ΦF value is the ratio of emitted photons to absorbed photons. This parameter is crucial for evaluating the effectiveness of these complexes as sensitizers in photodynamic and/or sono-photodynamic therapy [40,41]. In this study, fluorescence assessments were conducted using solutions of synthesized phthalocyanine compounds in DMSO, with an absorbance level of around 0.5. Fig. 6
                         shows the absorption, fluorescence excitation and emission spectra of 2a and 2b. The absorption spectrum indicates the wavelengths of light absorbed by the compound. Meanwhile, the excitation spectrum identifies the wavelengths of light that cause the compound to become excited. The emission spectrum displays the wavelengths of light that are emitted by the compound following excitation.The fluorescence quantum efficiency of the compound 2a is the same as the unsubstituted ZnPc we used as a standard, and it is ΦF = 0.20 [42] and 2b was measured as ΦF = 0.24 (Table 1
                        ). Low fluorescence emission enhances intersystem crossing, a process where molecules transition between different energy states. This increased intersystem crossing allows molecules to move into higher-energy triplet states, resulting in higher levels of singlet oxygen formation, which is crucial for the effectiveness of photodynamic therapy.
